---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout title="General Survey – Health Assessment">
  <h1>General Survey</h1>
  <p><em>Head-to-Toe Assessment Component · Section 1: Health Assessment</em></p>
  <p>
    The general survey is the <strong>first and broadest component</strong> of a head-to-toe
    assessment. It provides an overall impression of the patient before any focused examination.
  </p>

  <h2 id="loc">Level of Consciousness (LOC)</h2>
  <p>
    LOC describes the patient's degree of wakefulness and awareness of the environment.
    Always document LOC using a recognized scale or descriptor.
  </p>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Term</th><th>Description</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><strong>Alert</strong></td><td>Awake, attentive, responds appropriately to verbal stimuli</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Lethargic</strong></td><td>Drowsy but arousable; slow responses; may fall back asleep</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Obtunded</strong></td><td>Reduced alertness; responds only to strong stimuli; confused when awake</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Stuporous</strong></td><td>Arousable only with vigorous stimuli; minimal purposeful response</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Comatose</strong></td><td>Unresponsive to all stimuli; no purposeful movement</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2 id="appearance">Appearance</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Posture:</strong> Erect vs. slouched, guarded positions suggesting pain.</li>
    <li><strong>Body habitus:</strong> Underweight, normal weight, overweight, or obese; note apparent age vs. stated age.</li>
    <li><strong>Clothing:</strong> Appropriate for weather and situation; signs of neglect or poverty.</li>
    <li><strong>Grooming:</strong> Hair, nails, skin — clean and well-kept, or unkempt.</li>
    <li><strong>Facial expression:</strong> Relaxed, anxious, grimacing, flat.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="affect">Affect &amp; Behavior</h2>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Affect Type</th><th>Description</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><strong>Appropriate</strong></td><td>Emotional response matches context and content of speech</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Blunted</strong></td><td>Reduced intensity of emotional expression</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Flat</strong></td><td>Absence of emotional expression; monotone, expressionless</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Labile</strong></td><td>Rapid, unpredictable mood swings</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Euphoric</strong></td><td>Elevated, expansive mood; may be inappropriate to situation</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Anxious</strong></td><td>Apprehensive; may show fidgeting, hyperventilation, diaphoresis</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2 id="hygiene">Hygiene</h2>
  <p>
    Assess overall cleanliness and self-care ability. Poor hygiene may indicate
    inability to care for self (physical or cognitive impairment), substance abuse,
    depression, or social neglect. Document objectively without judgment:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Body odor present or absent</li>
    <li>Hair: clean vs. matted/unwashed</li>
    <li>Skin: clean vs. soiled; evidence of poor wound care</li>
    <li>Oral hygiene: moist mucosa vs. dry, cracked lips or coated tongue</li>
    <li>Clothing: clean vs. soiled or malodorous</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="distress">Distress</h2>
  <p>
    Document whether the patient is in apparent distress and characterize its nature:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>No apparent distress (NAD):</strong> Patient comfortable, breathing easily, not grimacing.</li>
    <li><strong>Mild distress:</strong> Slight discomfort; functional; able to answer questions without difficulty.</li>
    <li><strong>Moderate distress:</strong> Visibly uncomfortable; grimacing; limited by pain or dyspnea.</li>
    <li><strong>Acute/severe distress:</strong> Unable to focus; crying; labored breathing; immediate intervention needed.</li>
    <li><strong>Chronic distress:</strong> Long-standing pain or illness behavior; bracing, guarding posture.</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="tip">
    <strong>💡 Clinical Pearl</strong>
    Document the general survey findings in objective terms. Instead of "patient looks sick,"
    write "patient appears pale, diaphoretic, and in moderate respiratory distress." Specific,
    observable language supports accurate clinical communication.
  </div>

  <h2 id="documentation">Documentation Example</h2>
  <div class="note">
    <strong>📝 Sample Charting</strong>
    "Patient is a 72-year-old female, alert and oriented ×4, appearing her stated age. She is
    in no apparent distress. Posture is erect. Grooming is appropriate. Clothing is clean and
    seasonally appropriate. Affect is appropriate."
  </div>
</Layout>
